  "response": "Here's how particles are arranged in solids, liquids, and gases:\n\nSolids:\n- Particles are tightly packed together\n- Particles vibrate in fixed positions\n- Have a definite shape and volume\n- Strong forces of attraction between particles\n- Particles cannot move freely\n\nLiquids:\n- Particles are close together but can move around each other\n- Particles are less tightly packed than in solids\n- Take the shape of their container\n- Have a definite volume\n- Weak forces of attraction between particles\n- Particles can flow and move more freely\n\nGases:\n- Particles are spread far apart\n- Particles move randomly and quickly\n- No fixed shape or volume\n- Very weak forces of attraction between particles\n- Particles can spread out and move freely\n- Easily compressed\n\nKey differences relate to:\n- Spacing between particles\n- Strength of forces between particles\n- Particle movement\n- Ability to maintain shape and volume\n\nThese arrangements explain the different properties of solids, liquids, and gases.",
